==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grim
<hw>Grim</hw> <pr>(gr⟦icr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Grimmer</adjf> <pr>(-m⟦etil⟧r)</pr>;
superl. <adjf>Grimmest</adjf> <pr>(-m⟦ecr⟧st)</pr>.]</amorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>grim</ets>; akin to G. <ets>grimm</ets>, equiv. to G. & D.
<ets>grimmig</ets>, Dan. <ets>grim</ets>, <ets>grum</ets>, Sw.
<ets>grym</ets>, Icel. <ets>grimmr</ets>, G. <ets>gram</ets> grief, as
adj., hostile; cf. Gr. <?/, a crushing sound, <?/ to neigh.]</ety>
<def>Of forbidding or fear-inspiring aspect; fierce; stern; surly;
cruel; frightful; horrible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose <qex>grim</qex> aspect sets every joint a-shaking.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ridges of <qex>grim</qex> war.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b>-- Fierce; ferocious; furious; horrid; horrible;
frightful; ghastly; grisly; hideous; stern; sullen; sour.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grimace</ent>⟦br⟧
